lauren ginsberg reading the aeneid in octavia's rome stanford department of classics skip to navigation department of classics standford university logo header home people programs courses projects news events resources contact lauren ginsberg reading the aeneid in octavia's rome thursday february 2 2012 5 00 7 00 pm building 110 room 112 as the octavia's plot asks us toreflect on the historical significance of the fall of the julio claudian dynasty its language suggests that we reexamine the literature that had heralded the dynasty's rise in particular this talk explores how the play engages with the aeneid's primacy as a foundational epic of julio claudian empire and asks us to variously reinterpret the epic for a rome without augustus family lauren donovan ginsberg graduated from brown university in may 2011 and currently teaches at bucknell university her interests include latin literature especially drama epic and historiography and the intersection between literary and cultural memory studies login to post comments email stanford classics find us on facebook address & phone search upcoming events justin leidwanger defining economic regionalism an archaeology of maritime networks in the roman east 01 30 2012 lauren ginsberg reading the aeneid in octavia's rome 02 02 2012 see more recent news faculty grad student group awarded funding for shc research worshop 05 20 2011 stanford classics tops national research council rankings 09 28 2010 scit's production of aristophanes wasps in the spotlight 02 14 2011 see more news site info 2012 stanford university department of classics all rights reserved site design by chapter three login login with sunet speaker request webform for faculty stanford classics wikisite powered by drupal an open source content management system
